# Homepage hero — **LOCKED to a single photo** (TK approved)

## Absolute lock

The Super6 homepage hero is **one** full-bleed photograph. Not two slots.
Not a triptych. Not a carousel. Not a video.

The photo is **`/media/uploads/celtics-super6.jpg`** (Celtics #7 matchup —
green jersey ball-handler vs grey-camo defender on the hardwood).

It lives in **`super6-website/src/components/modules/HeroTileGrid.tsx`** as a
single `<Image>` inside `<div className="editorial-hero-media">` — no
`editorial-hero-media--split` modifier, no second `<Image>`, no `<video>`.

Unless **Timothy (TK) explicitly asks** for a change here, **do not**:

- Re-introduce `editorial-hero-media--split` on this hero
- Add a second `<Image>` slot (split / dual / triptych / carousel)
- Replace `celtics-super6.jpg` with a different file
- Convert the hero to a video, GIF, slideshow, or animated background
- Remove the `priority`, `fill`, or `sizes="100vw"` props on the `<Image>`
  (those props are required for mobile responsiveness and LCP)
- Wrap the `<Image>` in a swiper / framer-motion / animation library
- Move the hero outside `HeroTileGrid.tsx` or rename the component

## You may freely edit (still TK's design call, but no rule violation)

- `objectPosition` on the hero `<Image>` (focal anchor for re-cropped photos)
- `quality` on the hero `<Image>`
- The headline copy inside `<span className="hero-headline-taglock">`
  (currently "Where Champions" / "Are Made…")
- The meta strip text (currently "FL · GA · Since 2014")
- Photo grade / ken-burns timings via `globals.css` `.editorial-hero-media`
  rules — but only if the change applies to a single image (don't add
  `--split` selectors for new variants)

## Why this is locked

TK looked at split variations multiple times during the May 2026 design
sessions and explicitly chose the single-photo `celtics-super6.jpg` as the
canonical opening moment. The split version was reverted on TK's request
and replaced with this lock to prevent the layout from drifting back.

The Celtics #7 photo is the brand's emotional anchor — youth basketball
player in motion, defender reading him, real game energy, no posed shoot.
That's the Super 6 promise in one frame.

## Mobile responsiveness (already implemented)

- `fill` + `sizes="100vw"` → the photo fills any viewport width
- `objectFit: cover` → no letterboxing
- `objectPosition: "55% 30%"` → keeps the dribbler centered on phones
  while preserving heads above the bottom-of-frame scrim
- The headline and meta strip use `clamp()` typography in `globals.css`
  and stack cleanly down to 375px

If you reframe the photo (different crop, different subject, different
file), re-tune `objectPosition` so the focal subject sits in the safe
area at 375px width — but keep the locked single-image structure.

